    "ComparisonOur model (version 3) performance is compared to the performance of a well-known method, item-to-item collaborative filtering, as it was implemented by Linden et al. [38]; a system that, as they state, can scale to massive datasets.",
    "So, we run their algorithm on the AMiner Citation Network dataset, the same as we run the experiments of the proposed RS.Firstly, we selected the most common authors in the dataset (top one million authors that have liked/referenced the most papers), because the dataset is extremely sparse, with the 3.5 million authors.",
    "We mention, indicatively, the original's datasets mean values: each paper has only 20 ratings and each author has about 30 papers rated that gives a sparsity of 99.999%.",
    "The process of the 1 M most common authors filtering resulted to a small reduction in the total papers, from 5.3M to 4.9M and, of course, a reduction to 1 M authors.",
    "At this stage, we have a sparsity of 99.98% which is a minor improvement."
  ],
